# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arroz-a-la-valenciana
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] A **3-in-1**, **trio** or **three-in-one** is a fast-food dish consisting of chips, boiled rice (or egg fried rice), and curry sauce served in a single foil tray or plastic container.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] It became popular in Ireland as a dish from chip shops and Chinese restaurants in the early twenty-first century.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] It developed a cult following in the 2010s, and media outlets debated the merits of it compared to a spice bag, which became popular around the same time.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] Related dishes (four-, five-in one) contain additional ingredients such as chicken balls, or chicken or beef pieces.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Each region in Africa has developed its own distinctive culinary practices, shaped by local ingredients, colonial history and trade.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] In **West Africa,** for example, dishes often feature rice, millet, and beans complemented by spicy stews made with fish, meat, and leafy greens.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The use of chili peppers, peanuts and palm oil is also widespread in this region.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] **Central African** cuisine on the other hand, tends to be simpler and relies heavily on starchy foods such as cassava and plantains, often served with sauces made with peanuts or vegetables.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] In **East Africa**, particularly in countries like Kenya, Tanzania, and Uganda, the cuisine reflects a combination of native agricultural practices and influences from trade routes with India and the Middle East.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Staples such as maize, beans, and rice are commonly consumed along with dishes like Ugali (a maize-based porridge) and sukuma wiki (a dish made from collard greens).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The coastal areas of East Africa, particularly along the Swahili coast, feature seafood and curries seasoned with spices such as cardamom and cloves, a direct influence of Indian and Arab traders.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] **Southern African** cuisine also displays a blend of indigenous ingredients and colonial influences.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Dishes such as pap (a maize-based porridge) and biltong (a type of sausage) are popular in countries like South Africa, Botswana, and Namibia.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The cuisine is characterized by the use of game meat, maize, and beans, as well as European influences introduced during colonial times.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Traditionally, the various **cuisines of Africa** use a combination of plant-and seed-based ingredients, without having food imported.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] In some parts of the continent, the traditional diet features an abundance of root tuber products.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Africa represents a rich history of adaptation, trade, and resourcefulness. while regional differences are pronounced, the use of local ingredients and traditional cooking techniques remains central to the continent's culinary identity.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Central Africa, East Africa, North Africa, Southern Africa and West Africa each have distinctive dishes, preparation techniques, and consumption modes.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The roots of native African cuisine goes back to thousands of years before the Bronze Age in Northeast Africa, when early civilizations began cultivating grains such as barley and wheat.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Part of North Africa is in the Fertile Crescent where settled agriculture was practiced by the Ancient Egyptians in this area.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Animals such as donkeys and sheep were also domesticated, starting the spread of agriculture to other parts of Africa, notably West Africa.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Although most tribes still lived a simple hunter-gather diet.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Arab explorers- Leo Africanus and Ibn Battuta- provided accounts of African food which they encountered on their travels through sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Most European travelers stayed close to coastal areas until the 19th century.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Many of their diaries also recorded details on foods and crops.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Many staples were introduced later when Africa was colonized by the Europeans.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Foods that are now important parts of African cuisine such as maize and potatoes were not common until the 19th century.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The influence of African food on Caribbean, Brazilian, American Lowcountry cuisine, and Cajun cuisine from Louisiana is seen in rice dishes and green stews like the Afro-Caribbean efo, duckanoo and callaloo.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The vegetable okra, introduced from Africa, is used in classic Louisiana gumbos, and American rice growing in the Carolina.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Lowcountry was influenced by West African techniques of rice cultivation and many slaves hailed from the rice-growing regions of West Africa.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Lowcountry cuisine is still known for its distinctive rice dishes.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Central Africa expands from the Tibesti Mountains in the north to the vast rainforest basin of the Congo River, the highlands of Kivu and the savannah of Katanga.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] This region has received the culinary influence of the Swahilis (culture that evolved via the combination of Bantu, Yemeni, Omani and Indian cultures) during the trans-Saharan slave trade.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Swahili culinary influences can be found in dishes such as mandazi, pilaf rice, kachumbari, sambusa, and kuku paka.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Central African cuisine has also been influenced by the Portuguese, by way of the Kongo and Ndongo Kingdoms.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Salt fish was introduced following trade in the late 17th century, and the Kikongo term for salt fish, makayabu, comes from the Portuguese term bacalhau.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The Portuguese culinary influence is especially prominent in Angola, Sao Tomé and Equatorial Guinea.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Central Africa has also been influenced by the cuisine of the East, West and Southern Africa regions because of their close proximity, e.g. babuté or bobotie is shared with the south, nyama choma with the east and sauce gombo with West Africa.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] In Central Africa, a variety of crops are grown, including yams, cassava, bananas and plantains, sweet potatoes, and cocoyams.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] These crops have become staples in the diet of many people in Central Africa.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Fufu-like starchy foods are usually made from fermented cassava roots, but they can also be made with plantain, corn maize and yam.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Fufu is served buffet-style with grilled meat, fish, stews, greens and piment .
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] A variety of local ingredients are used while preparing other dishes, like spinach stew cooked with tomato, peppers, chilies, onions, and peanut butter.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Eastern central Africa is also one of the few regions in Africa that uses potatoes as one of its main bases, since potatoes grow easily in the region.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Cassava plants are also consumed as cooked greens.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Groundnut (peanut) stew is also prepared, containing chicken, okra, ginger, and other spices.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Beef and chicken are favorite meat dishes, but game meat preparations containing crocodile, elephant, antelope and warthog meats are also served occasionally.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The cuisine of East Africa varies from area to area.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] In the inland savannah, the traditional cuisine of cattle-keeping peoples is distinctive meaning that meat products are generally absent.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Cattle, sheep, pigs and goats were regarded as a form of currency and a store of wealth.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] They are not generally consumed as food.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] In some areas, traditional East Africans consume the milk and blood of cattle, but rarely the meat.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Elsewhere, other Africans are farmers who grow a variety of grains and vegetables.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Maize (corn) is the basis of ugali', the local version of West and Central Africa's fufu.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Ugali is a starch dish eaten with meats or stews.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] In Uganda, steamed green bananas called matoke provide the starch filler of many meals.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Around 1000 years ago, Omani and Yemeni merchants settled on the Swahili Coast.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Middle Eastern influences are especially reflected in the Swahili cuisine of the coast—steamed or cooked rice with spices in Persian style; saffron, cloves, cinnamon and several other spices; and pomegranate juice.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Several centuries later, the British and the Indians came, and both brought with them foods such as Indian spiced vegetable curries, lentil soups, chapattis and a variety of pickles which have influenced various local dishes.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Some common ingredients used in this region include oranges, lemons, limes, chilies, capsicum peppers, maize, tomatoes, and strawberries.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] In the Horn of Africa, the main traditional dishes in Eritrean cuisine and Ethiopian cuisine are tsebhis (stews) served with injera (flatbread made from teff, wheat, or sorghum) and hilbet (paste made from legumes, mainly lentils and fava beans).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Eritrean and Ethiopian cuisine (especially in the northern half) are very similar, given the shared history of the two countries.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Eritrean and Ethiopian food habits vary regionally.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] In the highlands, injera is the staple diet and is eaten daily among the Tigrinya.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Injera is made out of teff, wheat, barley, sorghum or corn, and resembles a spongy, slightly sour pancake.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] When eating, diners generally share food from a large tray placed in the center of a low dining table.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Many injera are layered on this tray and topped with various spicy stews.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Diners then break into the section of injera in front of them, tearing off pieces and dipping them into the stews.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] In the lowlands, the main dish is akelet, a porridge-like dish made from wheat flour dough.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] A ladle is used to scoop out the top, which is filled with berbere and butter sauce and surrounded by milk or yoghurt.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] A small piece of dough is broken and then used to scoop up the sauce.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The best known Ethiopian/Eritrean cuisine consists of various vegetable or meat side dishes and entrées, usually a wat, or thick stew, served atop injera, a large sourdough flatbread made of teff flour.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] One does not eat with utensils, but instead uses injera to scoop up the entrées and side dishes.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Tihlo, prepared from roasted barley flour, is very popular in Amhara, Agame, and Awlaelo (Tigray).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Traditional Ethiopian cuisine employs no pork or shellfish of any kind, as they are forbidden in the Jewish and Ethiopian Orthodox Christian faiths.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] It is also very common to eat from the same dish in the center of the table with a group of people.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Somali cuisine varies from region to region and consists of an exotic mixture of diverse culinary influences.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] It is the product of Somalia's rich tradition of trade and commerce.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Despite the variety, there remains one thing that unites the various regional cuisines: all food is served halal.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] There are therefore no pork dishes, alcohol is not served, nothing that died on its own is eaten, and no blood is incorporated.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Varieties of bariis (rice), the most popular being basmati, usually serve as the main dish.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Spices like cumin, cardamom, cloves, cinnamon and sage are used to aromatize these different rice dishes.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] During Ramadan, dinner is often served after Tarawih prayers, sometimes as late as 11 pm.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Xalwo (halwo) or halva is a popular confection served during special occasions such as Eid celebrations or wedding receptions.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] It is made from sugar, cornstarch, cardamom powder, nutmeg powder, and ghee.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Peanuts are also sometimes added to enhance texture and flavor.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] After meals, homes are traditionally perfumed using frankincense (lubaan) or incense (cuunsi), which is prepared inside an incense burner referred to as a dabqaad.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Food and nutrition security in East Africa (Rwanda, Burundi and South Sudan) is a significant issue.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The region has been plagued by drought, conflict and economic instability since the 1990s.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The current situation is characterized by low levels of food availability and high levels of malnutrition among young children.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The solution proposed for this problem is to increase local food production.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] This would be achieved by increasing agricultural productivity by improving soil fertility and water management, which will help farmers grow more crops per year.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] This will also help reduce poverty in the region by providing more employment opportunities for local people.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] In a study of food loss and waste in North Africa, researchers found that the region was wasting about 30% of its food, which is likely to increase as the population continues to grow.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] This waste occurs for a variety of reasons, including lack of refrigeration and storage facilities.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] To solve this issue, the people had to get creative with new dishes and ways of storing food.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The more we looked, the more we found that people were using all parts of plants in some way—the leaves, stems, flowers, fruits and seeds.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] They also used every edible part of animals as well—from fat to bones for making broth or soup.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] North Africa lies along the Mediterranean Sea and encompasses within its fold several nations, including Morocco, Algeria, Libya, Tunisia, and Egypt.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The roots of North African cuisine can be traced back to the ancient empires of North Africa, particularly in Egypt, where many of the country's dishes and culinary traditions date back to African antiquity.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Over several centuries traders, travelers, invaders, migrants and immigrants all have influenced the cuisine of North Africa.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The Phoenicians of the 1st century brought sausages, while the Carthaginians introduced wheat and its by-product, semolina.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The Berbers adapted semolina into couscous, one of the main staple foods.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Olives and olive oil were introduced before the arrival of the Romans.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] From the 7th century onwards, the Arabs introduced a variety of spices, like saffron, nutmeg, cinnamon, ginger and cloves, which contributed and influenced the culinary culture of North Africa.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The Ottoman Turks brought sweet pastries and other bakery products, and from the New World, North Africa got potatoes, tomatoes, zucchini and chili peppers.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] In addition, two completely different dishes may also share the same name (for example, a tajine dish is a slow-cooked stew in Morocco, whereas the Tunisian tajine is a baked omelette/quiche-like dish).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] There are noticeable differences between the cooking styles of different nations, from the sophisticated, full-bodied flavors of Moroccan palace cookery to the fiery dishes of Tunisian cuisine and the humbler, simpler cuisines of Egypt and Algeria.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The cooking of the Southern Africa region (not to be confused with the country of South Africa) is sometimes called "rainbow cuisine", as the food in this region is a blend of many cultures: indigenous African societies, European, and Asian.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] To understand indigenous African cuisine, it is important to understand the various native peoples of southern Africa.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The indigenous Africans of Southern Africa were roughly divided into two groups and several subgroups.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The largest group consisted of the Bantu-speakers, whose descendants today may identify themselves by various subgroup names such as Ndebele (northern and southern), Shona, Venda, Zulu, Xhosa, Swazi, Sotho, Tswana, Pedi and Tsonga.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] They arrived in the region around 2,000 years ago, bringing crop cultivation, animal husbandry, and iron toolmaking with them.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Hence the Bantu-speakers grew grain crops extensively and raised cattle, sheep and goats.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] They also grew and continue to grow pumpkins, beans, and leafy greens as vegetables.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] A smaller group were the primeval residents of the region, the Khoisan, who some archaeologists believe had lived in the region for at least 10,000 years.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Many descendants of the Khoisan people have now been incorporated into the population of South Africa.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The Khoisan originally were hunter-gatherers (who came to be known as "San" by the Bantu-speakers and as "bushmen" by Europeans).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] After the arrival of the Bantu-speakers, however, some Khoisan adopted the Bantu-speakers' raising of cattle but did not grow crops.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] People were, in other words, defined to some extent by the kinds of food they ate.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The Bantu-speakers ate dishes of grain, meat, milk and vegetables, as well as fermented grain and fermented milk products.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] While the Khoi-Khoi ate meat and milk and the San hunted wild animals and gathered wild tubers and vegetables.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] In many ways, the daily food of native South African families can be traced to the indigenous foods that their native African ancestors ate.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The Khoisan and Bantu traditionally ate roasted meat, and they also dried meat for later use.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The influence of their diet is reflected in the universal Southern African love of barbecue (generally called in South Africa by its Afrikaans name, a "braai") and biltong (dried preserved meat).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The traditional beer was ubiquitous in the southern African diet, and the fermentation added additional nutrients to the diet.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] It was a traditional obligation for any family to be able to offer a visitor copious amounts of beer.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Beer brewing was done by women, and the status of a housewife in pre-colonial southern Africa depended significantly on her skill at brewing delicious beer.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Milk was historically one of the most important components of the southern African diet.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Cattle were considered a man's most important possession.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] In order to marry, a man had to compensate his prospective in-laws with a gift of cattle as a dowry for his bride.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] A married man was expected to provide a generous supply of milk to his wife and children, along with meat whenever he slaughtered cattle, sheep or goats.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Because there was no refrigeration, milk was mostly soured into a kind of yogurt.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The young men of the family often took care of the cattle far away from the villages at "cattle posts," and they sent a steady stream of yogurt home on behalf of their fathers.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Today, many South Africans of African origin enjoy drinking sour milk products that are sold in the supermarket, comparable to American buttermilk, yogurt, and sour cream.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] On weekends they will have a "braai", and the meal usually consists of "pap and vleis", which is maize porridge and grilled meat as has historically been done in the region.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The basic ingredients include seafood, meat products (including wild game), poultry, as well as grains, fresh fruits and vegetables.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Fruits include apples, grapes, mangoes, bananas, papayas, avocado, oranges, peaches and apricots.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Desserts may simply be fruit, but there are some more western-style puddings, such as malva pudding, reminiscent of sticky toffee pudding, which was inspired by both British cuisine and Dutch cuisine.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Meat products include lamb, and game like venison, ostrich, and impala.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The seafood includes crayfish, prawns, tuna, mussels, oysters, calamari, mackerel, and lobster.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] There are also several types of traditional and modern alcoholic beverages including many European-style beers.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] A typical West African meal is made with starchy items and can contain meat, fish, as well as various spices and herbs.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] A wide array of staples are eaten across the region, including fufu, banku, kenkey (originating from Ghana), foutou, couscous, tô, and garri, which are served alongside soups and stews.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Fufu is often made from starchy root vegetables such as yams, cocoyams, or cassava, and also from cereal grains like millet, sorghum or plantains.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The staple grain or starch varies between regions and ethnic groups, although corn has gained significant ground as it is cheap, swells to greater volumes and creates a beautiful white final product that is greatly desired.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Banku and kenkey are maize dough staples, and garri is made from dried grated cassavas.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Rice dishes are also widely eaten in the region, especially in the dry Sahel belt inland.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Examples of these include the Senegalese dish thieboudienne also known as benachin or Jollof rice, a pan-West African rice dish similar to Arab kabsah.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Seeds of Guinea pepper (Aframomum melegueta, also called grains of paradise or melegueta pepper), a native West African plant, were used as a spice and even reached Europe, through North African middlemen, during the Middle Ages.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Centuries before the influence of the Europeans, West Africans were trading with the Arab world and spices like cinnamon, cloves, and mint were not unknown, therefore becoming part of the local flavorings.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Centuries later, the Portuguese, French and British influenced the regional cuisines, but only to a limited extent.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Cooking techniques include roasting, baking, boiling, frying, mashing, and spicing.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] A range of sweets and savories are also prepared.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Cooking techniques of West Africa are changing.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] In the past West Africans ate much less meat and used native oils (palm oil on the coast and shea butter in Sahelian regions).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Baobob leaf and numerous local greens were everyday staples during certain times of the year.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Today the diet is much heavier in meats, salt, and fats.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Many dishes combine fish and meat, including dried and fermented fish.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Flaked and dried fish is often fried in oil, and sometimes cooked in sauce made with hot peppers, onions, tomatoes, various spices (such as soumbala), and water to prepare a highly flavored stew.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] In some areas beef and mutton are preferred, and goat meat is the dominant red meat.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Suya, a popular grilled spicy meat kebab flavored with peanuts and other spices, is sold by street vendors as a snack or evening meal and is typically made with beef or chicken.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] It is common to have a preponderance of seafood, which as earlier stated, is sometimes also mixed with other meat products.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Guinea fowl and chicken eggs are also preferred.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] With regard to beverages, water has a very strong ritual significance in many West African nations (particularly in dry areas) and water is often the first thing an African host will offer their guest.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Palm wine is also a common beverage made from the fermented sap of various types of palm trees and is usually sold in sweet (less-fermented, retaining more of the sap's sugar) or sour (fermented longer, making it stronger and less sweet) varieties.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The exact origins of Bitter Leaf soup appear to be unknown thought it is known to have been prepared and eaten for hundreds of years.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The dish traditionally consists of fish, meat (usually beef), bitter leaves, palm oil, and an array of spices and seasonings.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Shellfish such as shrimp or crayfish are often used alongside fish in the preparation of Bitter Leaf Soup.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] Due to the bitterness of bitter leaf, the bitter leaf is washed thoroughly to diminish the bitterness before being cooked with the rest of the ingredients.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] It is widely consumed in West Africa, especially Nigeria where it is associated with the Igbo people and referred to as Ofe Onugbu.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The Bitter Leaf itself is known scientifically as Vernonia amygdalina and is native to Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/african-cuisine] The bitter taste comes from the alkaloids contained within the plant.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/afritada] The name *afritada* is derived from Spanish *fritada* ("fried"), referring to the first step of the preparation in which the meat is pan-fried before simmering in the tomato sauce.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/afritada] Filipino *menudo* and *kaldereta* both use tomato sauce or banana ketchup.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/afritada] However, *menudo* includes sliced liver, while *kaldereta* exclusively uses goat meat or occasionally beef.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/afritada] *Igado* contains liver but no tomato sauce.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour dishes, sauces, and cooking methods have a long history in China.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] One of the earliest recordings of sweet and sour may come from *Shaowei Yanshi Dan* (Chinese: 燒尾宴食單; pinyin: *shāowěi yànshí dān*), a menu of the food served in Tang dynasty (618–907) "Shaowei banquet" festivals written in 708.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] It included many sweet and sour adjacent dishes and recorded that they were invented by Chancellor Wei Juyuan under Emperor Zhongzong of Tang when he hosted the Emperor at his house.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Some authors say that the original sweet and sour sauce (Chinese: 糖醋醬; pinyin: *tángcùjiàng*) came from the Chinese province of Henan, but the sauce in this area is a light vinegar and sugar mixture not resembling what most people, including the Chinese, would call sweet and sour.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Many places in China use a sweet and sour sauce as a dipping sauce for fish and meat rather than in cooking, as is common in Westernized Chinese cuisine.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] This style of using sauces is popular amongst Chinese who tie certain sauces to particular meats such as chili and soy for shrimp and vinegar and garlic for goose.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] There are, however, some dishes, such as the Cantonese sweet and sour pork or loong har kow (sweet and sour lobster balls), in which the meat is cooked and a sauce added to the wok before serving.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Not all dishes are cooked; some, such as "sweet and sour fruit and vegetable" salad from the eastern regions of China, also find their way in Chinese cuisine.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] This cold dish combines salad vegetables such as cucumber, tomato, bell pepper, and onion with a mixture of pineapple (or pear), vinegar, and sugar.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] In China, the sauces are traditionally made by mixing sugar or honey with a sour liquid such as rice vinegar or soy sauce and spices such as ginger and cloves.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Sometimes a paste made from tomatoes is used, but this is rare and normally restricted to Western cooking.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Cantonese sweet and sour sauce is the direct ancestor of the sauce of the same name in the West and was originally developed for sweet and sour pork.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] The late Hong Kong chef Leung King included the following as his sweet and sour sauce recipe: white rice vinegar, salt, Chinese brown candy, ketchup, Worcestershire sauce, and dark soy sauce.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] He suggests the more acidic white rice vinegar could be replaced with apple cider vinegar and that ketchup and Worcestershire sauce should be of renowned gourmet brands.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] The original Cantonese sweet and sour pork (traditional Chinese: 咕嚕肉; simplified Chinese: 咕噜肉; pinyin: *gūlūròu*; Cantonese Yale: *gūlōuyuhk*; lit.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] 'rumbling meat') is made with vinegar, preserved plums and hawthorn candy for an almost scarlet color and sweet-sour taste.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] A related Hong Kong/Cantonese-based dish is sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 生炒排骨; pinyin: *Shēngchǎo páigǔ*; Cantonese Yale: *sāangcháau pàaigwāt*; lit.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] The methods used are identical, with spareribs used instead of pork loin.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] A similar dish is gu lao rou or sweet and sour pork.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Originating in Suzhou, Jiangsu province, the squirrel-shaped Mandarin fish (Chinese: 松鼠鱖魚; pinyin: *Sōngshǔ Guìyú*) has a crisp skin but soft center.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] The fish body of *Siniperca chuatsi* is scored such that it fans out when cooked, similar in appearance to a bushy squirrel tail.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] The fish is served with a sweet and sour sauce drizzled on top and garnished with a little shrimp meat and dried bamboo shoots.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] A specialty of Shandong province, in particular the city of Jinan, the Yellow River carp is prepared by making diagonal slices partway through its flesh.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] It is next coated in corn flour, then deep-fried, causing the fish to curl and the slices to open out.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Finally, a sweet and sour sauce is poured over the cooked fish.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] This is one of the distinctive dishes typical of Shandong cuisine.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] A popular dish in Shanghai cuisine, sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 糖醋小排; pinyin: *tángcù xiǎopái*) are made using pork ribs that are lightly coated in cornstarch and seasoned before being fried and served in a sweet and sour sauce.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] In South Korea, a sweet and sour meat dish known as *tangsuyuk* (탕수육; 糖水肉) is one of the most popular Korean Chinese dishes.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Made with either pork or beef, the bite-sized pieces are usually coated with potato/sweet potato starch/cornstarch or glutinous rice flour and double-fried in oil.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] The dish is served with sweet and sour sauce, typically made by boiling vinegar, sugar, and water with a variety of fruits and vegetables like carrot, cucumber, onion, wood ear mushroom, and pineapple.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Starch slurry is used to thicken the sauce.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] The traditional Dalmatian dish Pašticada features prunes and sweet dessert wine (prošek) as the sweet components, and vinegar in the marinade for sourness.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour sauces have been used in English cuisine since the Middle Ages, with recipes for sweet and sour meat and fish in the 1390 cookery book *The Forme of Cury*.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, a sweet and sour sauce base made from sugar and vinegar is a gastrique.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] *Aigre-doux* is a sweet and sour sauce in general.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] According to food writer Arthur Schwartz, within Neapolitan cooking, sweet and sour was the dominant food pairing before the introduction of the tomato and the mass-uptake of pasta.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Preparations using the combination eaten in the modern cuisine include sweet and sour eggplant, but it is never used to flavour pasta dishes.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] In Filipino cuisine, sweet and sour sauces are known as **agre dulce** or **Filipino sweet and sour sauce**.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] They are made by mixing cornstarch with water, salt, sugar, and a tangy ingredient (typically tomato ketchup, banana ketchup, or pineapples).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] The mixture is brought to a boil then simmered until it thickens.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] The name means "sour-sweet" in Philippine Spanish, from Spanish *agrio* ("sour") and *dulce* ("sweet").
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] It is also known as *agri dulci* in Chavacano and the phrase can refer to dishes cooked with the sauce.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] *Agre dulce* is commonly used as a dipping sauce for appetizers like *lumpia* or *okoy*.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour chicken is a dish frequently served in Chinese restaurants in various countries in Oceania, Europe, North America, and South America and available at some restaurants in East Asia and Southeast Asia in an essentially identical version.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] The dish generally comprises cubes of white meat chicken deep-fried in batter and served with sweet and sour sauce.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Sometimes it is topped with pineapple, green pepper, carrot, or sweet pickles.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour pork is a Chinese dish particularly popular in Westernized Cantonese cuisine and may be found worldwide.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Several provinces in China produce various dishes that claim to be the ancestor, including a traditional Jiangsu dish called "pork in a sugar and vinegar sauce" (糖醋里脊; pinyin: táng cù lǐjǐ).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] The dish consists of deep-fried pork cut into bite-sized pieces and subsequently stir-fried in a more customized version of sweet and sour sauce made of sugar, ketchup, white vinegar, and soy sauce and additional ingredients including pineapple, green pepper (capsicum), and onion.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] In more elaborate preparations, the dish's tartness is controlled by requiring that Chinese white rice vinegar be used sparingly and using ketchups with less vinegary tastes, while some restaurants use unripe kiwifruits and HP sauce in place of vinegar.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Western cultures use sweet and sour sauce in two different ways.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Dishes can either include the sauce as an ingredient in cooking or use the sauce as a pour-over or dipping sauce for the meal.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Chinese restaurants in Western countries commonly serve battered and deep-fried chicken, pork, or shrimp with a sweet and sour sauce poured on top.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] It is also common to find the sweet and sour sauce cooked with sliced green peppers, onions, and pineapple before it is poured over the meat.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Many Western dishes involve cooking the meat with a variety of ingredients to make a complete sweet and sour dish in the manner of gu lo yuk.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] The most popular dishes are those of pork and shrimp.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, it has been developed contrary to traditional French cooking practices, and the preparation of sweet and sour sauce (Aigre-douce) often involves immersing the food in a plentiful amount of sauce.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Common in Western sweet and sour sauce is the addition of fruits such as pineapple and vegetables such as sweet pepper and green onions.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Traditional rice vinegar is becoming more readily available due to the increase in Asian food stores but a mixture of vinegar and dry sherry is often still used in sweet and sour dishes.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Also common is the use of cornstarch as a thickener for the sauce and tomato ketchup to give a stronger red color to the dish and to add a Western taste.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Most supermarkets across Europe and North America carry a range of prepared sweet and sour sauces for adding to stir-fry or dipping.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Primarily in North America, sweet and sour sauce is available as a dipping sauce at Chinese takeout establishments in small plastic packets or containers.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] In Britain, Thai-style sweet chili sauce has recently overtaken the previous popularity of Chinese-style sweet and sour sauce to the extent it can often be found at non-Asian establishments for a wide variety of Western-style snacks from fishcakes to chips and seafood such as calamari and prawns.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] A number of variations are used in barbecue cuisine, either homemade or prepared from a number of common brands.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] Besides American Chinese restaurants, popular fast food restaurants such as McDonald's, Burger King, and Wendy's carry their own proprietary brands of sweet and sour sauce packets.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/agre-dulce] These are commonly offered and used as a dipping sauce for chicken fingers and chicken nuggets.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] As a political domain, it successively constituted a province of the Umayyad Caliphate, initiated by the Caliph al-Walid I (711–750); the Emirate of Córdoba (c.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Under the Caliphate of Córdoba, the city of Córdoba became one of the leading cultural and economic centres throughout the Mediterranean Basin, Europe, and the Islamic world.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Achievements that advanced Islamic and Western science came from al-Andalus, including major advances in trigonometry (Jabir ibn Aflah), astronomy (al-Zarqali), surgery (al-Zahrawi), pharmacology (Ibn Zuhr), and agronomy (Ibn Bassal and Abu'l-Khayr al-Ishbili).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Al-Andalus became a conduit for cultural and scientific exchange between the Islamic and Christian worlds.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] For much of its history, al-Andalus existed in conflict with Christian kingdoms to the north.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] After the fall of the Umayyad Caliphate of Cordoba by 1031, al-Andalus was fragmented into *taifa* states and principalities, some of which (such as the Taifa of Toledo, the Taifa of Zaragoza, the Taifa of Seville and the Taifa of Badajoz) reached considerable territorial extent.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] After the Christian capture of Toledo in 1085, the Almoravid empire intervened and repelled attacks on the region, then brought al-Andalus under direct Almoravid rule.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] For the next century and a half, al-Andalus became a province of the Muslim empires of the Almoravids and their successors, the Almohads, both based in Marrakesh.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Ultimately, the northern Christian kingdoms overpowered the Muslim states to the south.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In the 13th century, most of the south quickly fell under Christian rule, with Gharb al-Andalus, the Guadalquivir Valley and Eastern al-Andalus falling to Portuguese, Castilian, and Aragonese conquests.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] This left the Emirate of Granada as the remaining Muslim state on the Iberian Peninsula, which became a tributary state of the Crown of Castile, before surrendering in 1492 to the Catholic Monarchs.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The toponym *al-Andalus* is first attested by inscriptions on coins minted in 716 by the new Muslim government of Iberia.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] These coins, called *dinars*, were inscribed in both Latin and Arabic.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The etymology of the name *al-Andalus* has traditionally been derived from the name of the Vandals (*vándalos* in Spanish, *vândalos* in Portuguese).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Since the 1980s, several alternative etymologies have challenged this tradition.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In 1986, Joaquín Vallvé proposed that *al-Andalus* was a corruption of the name *Atlantis*.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Heinz Halm in 1989 derived the name from a Gothic term, **landahlauts*, and in 2002, Georg Bossong suggested its derivation from a pre-Roman substrate.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] During the caliphate of the Umayyad Caliph Al-Walid I, the commander Tariq ibn-Ziyad led an army of 7,000 that landed at Gibraltar on April 30, 711, ostensibly to intervene in a Visigothic civil war.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] After a decisive victory over King Roderic at the Battle of Guadalete on 19 July 711, Tariq, accompanied by his *mawla*, governor Musa ibn Nusayr of Ifriqiya, brought most of the Visigothic Kingdom under Muslim rule in a seven-year campaign.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] They crossed the Pyrenees and occupied Visigothic Septimania in southern France.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Most of the Iberian peninsula became part of the expanding Umayyad Empire, under the name of *al-Andalus*.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] It was organised as a province subordinate to Ifriqiya, so, for the first few decades, the governors of al-Andalus were appointed by the emir of Kairouan, rather than the Caliph in Damascus.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The regional capital was set at Córdoba, and the first influx of Muslim settlers was widely distributed.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Following the Muslim conquest of Spain, al-Andalus, then at its greatest extent, was divided into five administrative units, corresponding very roughly to: modern Andalusia; Castile and León; Navarre, Aragon, and Catalonia; Portugal and Galicia; and the Languedoc-Roussillon area of Occitania.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The small army Tariq led in the initial conquest consisted mostly of Berbers, while Musa's largely Arab force of over 12,000 soldiers was accompanied by a group of *mawālī* (Arabic, موالي), that is, non-Arab Muslims, who were clients of the Arabs.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The Berber soldiers accompanying Tariq were garrisoned in the centre and the north of the peninsula, as well as in the Pyrenees, while the Berber colonists who followed settled in all parts of the country – north, east, south and west.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Visigothic lords who agreed to recognise Muslim suzerainty were allowed to retain their fiefs (notably, in Murcia, Galicia, and the Ebro valley).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Resistant Visigoths took refuge in the Cantabrian highlands, where they carved out a rump state, the Kingdom of Asturias.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In the 720s, the al-Andalus governors launched several *sa'ifa* raids into Aquitaine but were decisively defeated by Duke Odo the Great of Aquitaine at the Battle of Toulouse (721).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] At the Battle of Poitiers in 732, the al-Andalus raiding army was defeated by Charles Martel and Al Ghafiqi was killed.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In 734, the Andalusi launched raids to the east, capturing Avignon and Arles, and overran much of Provence.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In 737, they travelled up the Rhône valley, reaching as far north as Burgundy.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Charles Martel of the Franks, with the assistance of Liutprand of the Lombards, invaded Burgundy and Provence and expelled the raiders by 739.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In 740, a Berber Revolt erupted in the Maghreb (North Africa).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] To put down the rebellion, the Umayyad Caliph Hisham dispatched a large Arab army, composed of regiments (*Junds*) from Bilad Ash-Sham, to North Africa.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] This Umayyad army was defeated by the Berber rebels at the Battle of Bagdoura (in Morocco).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Heartened by the victories of their North African brethren, the Berbers of al-Andalus quickly raised their own revolt.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Berber garrisons in the north of the Iberian Peninsula mutinied, deposed their Arab commanders, and organised a large rebel army to march against the strongholds of Toledo, Córdoba, and Algeciras.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In 741, Balj bin Bishr led a detachment of some 10,000 Arab troops across the straits.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The Arab governor of al-Andalus, joined by this force, was victorious over the Berber rebels in a series of battles in 742.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] A dispute erupted between the Syrian commanders and the Andalusi, the so-called "original Arabs" of the earlier contingents.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The Syrians defeated them at the hard-fought Battle of Aqua Portora in August 742 but were too few to impose themselves on the province.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The Egypt jund was divided between Beja (Alentejo) in the west and Tudmir (Murcia) in the east.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The arrival of the Syrians substantially increased the Arab element in the Iberian peninsula and helped strengthen the Muslim hold on the south.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] However, at the same time, unwilling to be governed, the Syrian *junds* carried on an existence of autonomous feudal anarchy, severely destabilising the authority of the governor of al-Andalus.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] A second significant consequence of the revolt was the expansion of the Kingdom of the Asturias, hitherto confined to enclaves in the Cantabrian highlands.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] After the rebellious Berber garrisons evacuated the northern frontier fortresses, the Christian king Alfonso I of Asturias set about immediately seizing the empty forts for himself, quickly adding the northwestern provinces of Galicia and León to his fledgling kingdom.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The Asturians evacuated the Christian populations from the towns and villages of the Galician-Leonese lowlands, creating an empty buffer zone in the Douro River valley (the "Desert of the Duero").
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] This newly emptied frontier remained roughly in place for the next few centuries as the boundary between the Christian north and the Islamic south.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] On the Muslim side of the frontier, al-Andalus had three large march territories (*thaghr*, pl.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] These disturbances and disorder also allowed the Franks, now under the leadership of Pepin the Short, to invade the strategic strip of Septimania in 752, hoping to deprive al-Andalus of an easy launching pad for raids into Francia.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] After a lengthy siege, the last Arab stronghold, the citadel of Narbonne, finally fell to the Franks in 759.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Al-Andalus was sealed off at the Pyrenees.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The third consequence of the Berber revolt was the collapse of the authority of the Damascus Caliphate over the western provinces.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] With the Umayyad Caliphs distracted by the challenge of the Abbasids in the east, the western provinces of the Maghreb and al-Andalus spun out of their control.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] From around 745, the Fihrids, an illustrious local Arab clan descended from Oqba ibn Nafi al-Fihri, seized power in the western provinces and ruled them almost as a private family empire of their own – Abd al-Rahman ibn Habib al-Fihri in Ifriqiya and Yūsuf al-Fihri in al-Andalus.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The Fihrids welcomed the fall of the Umayyads in the east, in 750, and sought to reach an understanding with the Abbasids, hoping they might be allowed to continue their autonomous existence.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] But when the Abbasids rejected the offer and demanded submission, the Fihrids declared independence and, probably out of spite, invited the deposed remnants of the Umayyad clan to take refuge in their dominions.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] It was a fateful decision that they soon regretted, for the Umayyads, the sons and grandsons of caliphs, had a more legitimate claim to rule than the Fihrids themselves.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Rebellious-minded local lords, disenchanted with the autocratic rule of the Fihrids, conspired with the arriving Umayyad exiles.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In 755, the exiled Umayyad prince Abd al-Rahman I (also called *al-Dākhil*, the 'Immigrant') arrived on the coast of Spain.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] He had fled the Abbasids, who had overthrown the Umayyads in Damascus and were slaughtering members of that family, and then he spent four years in exile in North Africa, assessing the political situation in al-Andalus across the Straits of Gibraltar, before he landed at Almuñécar.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] News of his arrival spread across al-Andalus, and when word reached its governor, Yūsuf al-Fihri, he was not pleased.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] During this time, Abd al-Rahman and his supporters quickly conquered Málaga and then Seville, finally besieging the capital of al-Andalus, Córdoba.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Abd al-Rahman's army was exhausted after their conquest, meanwhile Governor Yūsuf al-Fihri had returned from quashing another rebellion with his army.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The siege of Córdoba began, and noticing the starving state of Abd al-Rahman's army, al-Fihri began throwing lavish feasts every day as the siege went on, to tempt Abd al Rahman's supporters to defect to his side.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] However, Abd al-Rahman persisted, even rejecting a truce that would have allowed Abd al-Rahman to marry al-Fihri's daughter.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] After decisively defeating Yūsuf al-Fihri's army, Abd al-Rahman was able to conquer Córdoba, where he proclaimed himself emir in 756.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The rest of al-Andalus was easily conquered, and Abd al-Rahman soon had control of all of al-Andalus.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] By far the most important of these invasions was the attempted reconquest by the Abbasid Caliphate.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In 763 Caliph Al-Mansur of the Abbasids installed al-Ala ibn-Mugith as governor of Africa (whose title gave him dominion over the province of al-Andalus).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] He planned to invade and destroy the Emirate of Córdoba, so in response Abd al Rahman fortified himself within the fortress of Carmona with a tenth as many soldiers as al-Ala ibn-Mugith.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] After a long siege, it appeared that Abd al Rahman would be defeated, but in a last stand Abd al Rahman with his outnumbered forces opened the gates of the fortress and charged at the resting Abbasid army, and decisively defeated them.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Abd al Rahman I died in 788 after a lengthy and prosperous reign.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] He was succeeded by his son, Hisham I, who secured power by exiling his brother who had tried to rebel against him.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Hisham enjoyed a stable reign of eight years and was succeeded by his son Al-Hakam I.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The next few decades were relatively uneventful, with only occasional minor rebellions, and saw the rise of the emirate.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In 822 Al Hakam died and was succeeded by Abd al-Rahman II, the first great emir of Córdoba.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] He rose to power with no opposition and sought to reform the emirate.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] He quickly reorganised the bureaucracy to be more efficient and built many mosques across the emirate.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] During his reign science and art flourished, as many scholars fled the Abbasid caliphate due to the disastrous Fourth Fitna.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The scholar Abbas ibn Firnas made an attempt to fly, though accounts vary on his success.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In 852 Abd al Rahman II died, leaving behind him a powerful and well-established state that had become one of the most powerful in the Mediterranean.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Abd al Rahman was succeeded by Muhammad I of Córdoba, who according to legend had to wear women's clothing to sneak into the imperial palace and be crowned, since he was not the heir apparent.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] His reign marked a decline in the emirate, which was ended by Abd al-Rahman III.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] His reign was marked by multiple rebellions, which were dealt with poorly and weakened the emirate, most disastrously following the rebellion of Umar ibn Hafsun.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] When Muhammad died, he was succeeded by emir Abdullah ibn Muhammad al-Umawi whose power barely reached outside of the city of Córdoba.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] As Ibn Hafsun ravaged the south, Abdullah did almost nothing, and slowly became more and more isolated, barely speaking to anyone.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Abdullah purged his administration of his brothers, which lessened the bureaucracy's loyalty towards him.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Around this time several local Arab lords began to revolt, including one Kurayb ibn Khaldun, who was able to conquer Seville.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Some loyalists tried to quell the rebellion, but without proper material support, their efforts were in vain.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] He declared that the next emir would be his grandson Abd al-Rahman III, ignoring the claims of his four living children.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Abdullah died in 912, and the throne passed to Abd al Rahman III.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Through force of arms and diplomacy, he put down the rebellions that had disrupted his grandfather's reign, obliterating Ibn Hafsun and hunting down his sons.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] After this he led several sieges against the Christians, sacking the city of Pamplona, and restoring some prestige to the emirate.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Meanwhile, across the sea the Fatimids had risen up in force, ousted the Abbasid government in North Africa, and declared themselves a caliphate.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Inspired by this action, Abd al Rahman joined the rebellion and declared himself caliph in 929.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] For nearly 100 years under the Córdoban Umayyad period, from the 9th century to the 10th, al-Andalus also extended its presence from Fraxinetum into the Alps with a series of organised raids.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The period of the Caliphate is seen as the golden age of al-Andalus.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Córdoba under the Caliphate, with a population of more than half a million, eventually overtook Constantinople as the largest and most prosperous city in the world.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Al-Andalus became a centre for the arts, medicine, science, music, literature and philosophy.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The work of its most important philosophers and scientists, such as Abulcasis and Averroes, had a major influence on the intellectual life of medieval Europe.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Muslims and non-Muslims often came from abroad to study at the libraries and universities of al-Andalus, and after the reconquest of Toledo, several translation institutions such as the Toledo School of Translators were established for translating books and texts from Arabic into Latin.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The most noted figures in this being Gerard of Cremona and Michael Scot, who took these works to Italy.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The transmission of ideas significantly affected the formation of the European Renaissance.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The Caliphate of Córdoba also had extensive trade with other parts of the Mediterranean, including Christian parts.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Trade goods included luxury items (silk, ceramics, gold), essential foodstuffs (grain, olive oil, wine), and containers (such as ceramics for storing perishables).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In the tenth century, Amalfitans were already trading Fatimid and Byzantine silks in Córdoba.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Later references to Amalfitan merchants were sometimes used to emphasise the previous golden age of Córdoba.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Fatimid Egypt was a supplier of many luxury goods, including elephant tusks, and raw or carved crystals.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The Fatimids were traditionally thought to be the only supplier of such goods, and control over these trade routes would be a cause for conflict between the Umayyads and Fatimids.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The Caliphate of Córdoba effectively collapsed during a ruinous civil war between 1009 and 1013, although it was not finally abolished until 1031 when *al-Andalus* broke up into a number of mostly independent mini-states and principalities called *taifas*.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In 1013, invading Berbers sacked Córdoba, massacring its inhabitants, pillaging the city, and burning the palace complex to the ground.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The largest of the taifas to emerge were Badajoz (*Batalyaws*), Toledo (*Ṭulayṭulah*), Zaragoza (*Saraqusta*), and Granada (*Ġarnāṭah*).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] During the eleventh century several centres of power existed among the taifas, and the political situation shifted rapidly.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The taifas were vulnerable and divided but had immense wealth.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] During its prominence the Taifa of Seville produced technically complex lusterware and exerted significant influence on ceramic production across al-Andalus.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In the 1080s, the *taifa* kingdoms began to face an existential threat from the Christian kingdoms to the north, as Alfonso VI of Castile escalated attacks against them.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In 1083, he led a punitive expedition against Seville that reached all the way to Tarifa at the southern tip of al-Andalus.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In 1085, he annexed Toledo, a turning point which galvanised the remaining *taifa* leaders into seeking outside help.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] After the fall of Toledo, most of the major *taifa* rulers agreed to request the intervention of the Almoravids, a Berber empire based in Marrakesh that had conquered much of northwest Africa.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The Almoravid leader, Yusuf Ibn Tashfin, led several campaigns into al-Andalus, initially in defence of the *taifa* kingdoms.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] At the Battle of Sagrajas (or Battle of Zallaqa in Arabic), a Muslim army led by the Almoravids soundly defeated Alfonso VI.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] By 1090, however, Yusuf ibn Tashfin was disillusioned with the disunity of the *taifa* leaders and he returned on a campaign to conquer al-Andalus instead.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Most of the *taifas*, except for Zaragoza, were annexed by 1094.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Valencia, which had come under the control of El Cid at the end of its taifa period, was eventually occupied in 1102, after El Cid's death.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The rise and fall of the Almoravids is sometimes seen as an expression of Ibn Khaldun's asabiyyah paradigm.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] By 1147, the Almoravids were overthrown in North Africa by the Almohads, another Berber dynasty, under the leadership of Abd al-Mu'min.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] As Almoravid rule collapsed, another brief period of *taifa* kingdoms followed in al-Andalus, during which the Christian kingdoms expanded southward again.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] From 1146 onward, the Almohads intervened and took control of al-Andalus.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] One of Abd al-Mu'min's successors, Ya'qub al-Mansur, won a major victory over the Castilian Alfonso VIII at the Battle of Alarcos in 1195.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In 1212, a coalition of Christian kings under the leadership of Alfonso VIII defeated the Almohads at the Battle of Las Navas de Tolosa.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Almohad rule was diminished in prestige and in 1228 the Almohad caliph al-Ma'mun withdrew from al-Andalus altogether.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In this political vacuum, a new wave of *taifa* kingdoms emerged, which were progressively conquered by Portugal, Castile, and Aragon.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Córdoba was conquered in 1236 and Seville was conquered in 1248.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Some Muslim city-states, such as Murcia and Niebla, survived as vassal kingdoms of Castile until the 1260s.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Only the region of Granada remained unconquered.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] From the mid 13th to the late 15th century, the only remaining domain of al-Andalus was the Emirate of Granada, the last Muslim stronghold in the Iberian Peninsula.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The emirate was established by Muhammad ibn al-Ahmar in 1230 and was ruled by the Nasrid dynasty, the longest reigning dynasty in the history of al-Andalus.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Although surrounded by Castilian lands, the emirate was wealthy through being tightly integrated in Mediterranean trade networks and enjoyed a period of considerable cultural and economic prosperity.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Despite internal conflicts, the Nasrids of Granada were able to survive in part by playing the Christian kingdoms of the north against each other, while at other times soliciting aid from the Marinids, a new Berber dynasty ruling in North Africa from their capital in Fez.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] For much of its existence, Granada paid tribute to the Castilian kings.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Along with this political status, its favourable geographic location, with the Sierra Nevada as a natural barrier, helped to prolong Nasrid rule.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Granada also accommodated a large number of Muslim refugees fleeing the *Reconquista* or expelled from Christian-controlled territories, which grew the city and the emirate's population.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The city even became one of the largest in Europe throughout the 15th century in terms of population.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The most visible legacy of the Nasrids is the Alhambra, their fortified palace complex, partly preserved today.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The independent Nasrid kingdom was also a trade hub between the Atlantic and Mediterranean, and was frequented especially by Genoese merchants.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The Marinids intervened in the south of the Iberian Peninsula multiple times up until their defeat at the Battle of Río Salado in 1340.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] After this, they ceased to play a major role.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The subsequent internal turmoil within Castile, however, helped Nasrid Granada to enjoy a period of relative external peace and internal prosperity until the end of the 14th century, under the reigns of Yusuf I (r.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Important cultural figures, such as Ibn al-Khatib, Ibn Zamrak, and Ibn Khaldun all served in the Nasrid court during this period.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In 1468, Isabella, the only child of Henry IV of Castile, married Ferdinand, the son of John II of Aragon, and by 1479 they were rulers of a united Castile and Aragon.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] This development meant that Granada could no longer exploit divisions between the two kingdoms and the new royal couple, also known as the Catholic Monarchs, were united in their intention to conquer it.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The final war to conquer Granada began in earnest in 1482.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Year by year, the Christian advance captured new cities and fortresses until the last Nasrid ruler, Muhammad XI (known as Boabdil to the Christians), formally surrendered Granada to the Catholic Monarchs on January 2, 1492.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] By this time Muslims in Castile numbered half a million.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] After the fall, "100,000 had died or been enslaved, 200,000 emigrated, and 200,000 remained as the residual population.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] From 1492 to 1493, tens of thousands of expulsed Muslims and Jews from al-Andalus were rescued when the Ottomans under orders of Sultan Bayezid II sent ships.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Thousands of Jews were transported to Ottoman lands, and many settled in North Africa.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Mass forced conversions of Muslims in 1499 led to a revolt that spread to Alpujarras and the mountains of Ronda; after this uprising the capitulations were revoked.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In 1502 the Catholic Monarchs decreed the forced conversion of all Muslims living under the rule of the Crown of Castile, although in the kingdoms of Aragon and Valencia (both now part of Spain) the open practice of Islam was allowed until 1526.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Descendants of the Muslims were subject to expulsions from Spain between 1609 and 1614 (see Expulsion of the Moriscos).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The last mass prosecution against Moriscos for crypto-Islamic practices occurred in Granada in 1727, with most of those convicted receiving relatively light sentences.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The Morisco community including these final convicts kept their identity alive at least through the late eighteenth century.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] There was much scientific activity in al-Andalus, especially in the fields of medicine, astronomy, mathematics, and agronomy.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] At the same time, Andalusi scholars were also highly active in philosophy (see below), especially in the field of logic.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The earliest evidence of such activities in al-Andalus dates to the reign of Abd ar-Rahman II (r.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] 822–852), when developments were spurred by exposure to older works translated from, Greek, Persian and other languages.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Scientific studies continued to be pursued in the following centuries, though certain fields and subjects thrived more depending on the period.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Scholars often worked in many different and overlapping subjects, so it is difficult to place those discussed here into a single scientific field each.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] There were many notable surgeons, physicians, and medical scholars from al-Andalus including Ibn al-Baytar (d.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] 1248), Abu al-Qasim al-Zahrawi (Albucasis; d.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] 1360), Abu Marwan 'Abd al-Malik ibn Habib (d.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] 853), and Abu Marwan ibn Zuhr (Avenzoar; d.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] This encyclopaedia is also significant for its inclusion of al-Zahrawi's personal experiences as a surgeon, which provided important case studies for aspiring surgeons.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] This distinguishes it from other strictly factual medical works of the time, most notably Ibn Sina's *Canon of Medicine*.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Ibn Habib's work is significant because it is one of the oldest known writings in the field of prophetic medicine, which uses hadiths to create Islamic-based medicinal guidelines.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] His book is also significant because it uses principles of Galenic medicine, such as humorism and the theory of four temperaments, as the basis of its medical recommendations.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The ibn Zuhr family played a very important role in the production of Andalusi medical knowledge, as they produced five generations of medical experts, particularly in the fields of dietary sciences and medicaments.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In *Kitab al-Taysir* he provides one of the earliest clinical descriptions of the scabies mite.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The Maristan of Granada was founded in 1367 by the Nasrid ruler Muhammad V of Granada and stands as one of the clearest examples of institutional medicine in late al-Andalus.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Established as a charitable hospital in the Islamic tradition, it provided care for the sick, including those suffering from mental illness, and was funded through religious endowment.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Contemporary sources describe it as a purpose-built structure organised around a central courtyard with water features, reflecting both hygienic and therapeutic concerns.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The maristan illustrates the integration of medical practice, urban planning, and social welfare in Nasrid Granada, continuing the broader Andalusi engagement with the classical medical heritage of figures such as Ibn Sina while adapting it to local needs.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The maristam has reopened in recent years as a museum for visitors.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Three of the most notable Andalusi astronomers were Ibn Tufail (d.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] 1198), and Nur ad-Din al-Bitruji (Alpetragius; d.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] All lived around the same time and focused their astronomical works on critiquing and revising Ptolemaic astronomy and the problem of the equant in his astronomical model.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Instead, they accepted Aristotle's model and promoted the theory of homocentric spheres.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Al-Bitruji is believed to have studied under Ibn Tufail and Bitruji's *Book on Cosmology* (*Kitab fi al-hay'a*) built on Ibn Tufail's work, as well as that of Ibn Rushd, Ibn Bajja, and Maimonides.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] The book's goal was "to overcome the physical difficulties inherent in the geometrical models of Ptolemy's *Almagest* and to describe the cosmos in agreement with Aristotelian or Neoplatonic physics," which it succeeded in doing to an extent.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Bitruji's book set a precedent of criticising the *Almagest* in future works in the field of astronomy.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Although Ibn Rushd originally trained and practiced as a jurist, he was exposed to astronomy—possibly through Ibn Tufail—and became a renowned scientist in the field.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] His most popular work was his *Summary of the Almagest*, but he also published shorter works discussing Aristotle's planetary theories.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Ibn Rushd published writings on philosophy, theology, and medicine throughout his life too, including commentaries on the works of Ibn Sina.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] In addition to writing the important *Book of the Medicine of the Arabs*, Ibn Habib also wrote the *Book on Stars* (*Kirab fi l-nujim*).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] This book included important "teachings on the lunar mansions, the signs of the zodiac, [and] the division of the seasons." In these teachings, Ibn-Habib calculated the phases of the moon and dates of the annual solstices and equinoxes with relative accuracy.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Another important astronomer from al-Andalus was Maslama al-Majriti (d.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] 1007), who played a role in translating and writing about Ptolemy's *Planisphaerium* and *Almagest*.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] He built on the work of older astronomers, like Muhammad ibn Musa al-Khwarizmi, whose astronomical tables he wrote a discussion on and subsequently improved.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] 1087) had many influential astronomical successes, as shown by Copernicus's recognition of him in his *On the Revolutions of the Heavenly Spheres* five centuries later.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Along with other astronomers, he undertook extensive work to edit the Toledan Zij astronomical tables.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] He also accurately calculated the motion of the solar apogee to be 12.04 seconds per year, which is relatively close to today's calculation of 11.8 seconds per year.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Other important scientific advances in al-Andalus occurred in the field of agronomy.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] These advances were in part facilitated by technological innovations in irrigation systems.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] State organised, large-scale irrigation projects provided water to city baths, mosques, gardens, residential homes, and governing palaces, such as the al-Hambra and its gardens in Granada.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Collective, peasant-built irrigation infrastructure also played an important role, especially in agriculture.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Many of these irrigation techniques, especially those utilised by peasants, were brought to al-Andalus by migrating Berber and Arab tribes.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Although some irrigation projects built on existing Roman infrastructure, most of al-Andalus's irrigation systems were new projects built separate from old Roman aqueducts.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] However, there is some debate about this among scholars.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] One notable agriculturalist was Ibn al-'Awwam, who wrote the *Book of Agriculture*.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] This book contains 34 chapters about various aspects of agriculture and animal husbandry, including discussions of over 580 different types of plants and how to treat plant diseases.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p01] Other agronomic innovations in al-Andalus include the cultivation of the pomegranate from Syria, which has since become the namesake and ubiquitous symbol of the city of Granada, as well as the first attempt to create a botanical garden near Córdoba by 'Abd al-Rahman I.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The society of al-Andalus was made up of three main religious groups: Muslims, Christians, and Jews.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The Muslims, although united on the religious level, had several ethnic divisions, the main being the distinction between the Arabs and the Berbers.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The Arab elite regarded non-Arab Muslims as second-class citizens; and they were particularly scornful of the Berbers.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The ethnic structure of al-Andalus consisted of Arabs at the top of the social scale followed by, in descending order, Berbers, Muladies, Mozarabes, and Jews.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Each of these communities inhabited distinct neighbourhoods in the cities.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] In the 10th century a massive conversion of Christians took place, and *muladies* formed the majority of Muslims.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Thomas Glick claims that Muladies, together with other Muslims, comprised eighty per cent of the population of al-Andalus by 1100.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Mozarabs were Christians who had long lived under Muslim and Arab rule, adopting many Arab customs, art and architecture, and words, while still maintaining their Christian and Latin rituals and their own Romance languages.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The Jewish population worked mainly as tax collectors, in trade, or as doctors or ambassadors.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] At the end of the 15th century there were about 50,000 Jews in Granada and roughly 100,000 in the whole of Islamic Iberia, which had been reduced to the territory of the Emirate of Granada.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Non-Muslims were given the status of *ahl al-dhimma* (people under protection), with adult men paying a "Jizya" tax equal to one dinar per year with exemptions for the elderly and the disabled.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Those who were neither Christians nor Jews, such as pagans, were given the status of *Majus*.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The treatment of non-Muslims in the Caliphate has been a subject of considerable debate among scholars and commentators, especially those interested in drawing parallels to the co-existence of Muslims and non-Muslims in the modern world.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Jews constituted more than five per cent of the population.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Al-Andalus was a key centre of Jewish life during the early Middle Ages, produced important scholars and was one of the most stable and wealthy Jewish communities.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Southern Iberia became an asylum for the oppressed Jews of other countries.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Under the Almoravids and the Almohads, there may have been intermittent persecution of Jews, but sources are extremely scarce and do not give a clear picture though the situation appears to have deteriorated after 1160.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Muslim pogroms against Jews in al-Andalus occurred in Córdoba (1011) and in Granada (1066).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] However, massacres of *dhimmis* are believed to be rare in Islamic history.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The Almohads, who had taken control of the Almoravids' Maghribi and Andalusi territories by 1147, far surpassed the Almoravides in fundamentalist outlook, and treated the non-Muslims harshly.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Faced with the choice of either death or conversion, many Jews and Christians emigrated.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Some, such as the family of Maimonides, fled east to more tolerant Muslim lands.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Many ethnicities and religions co-existed in al-Andalus, each of which contributed to its intellectual prosperity.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Literacy in Islamic Iberia was far more widespread than in many other nations in the West of the time.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Though the number of the early inhabitants of al-Andalus after the 7th-century conquest was small, many native Iberian inhabitants converted to Islam, known as *Muwalladun* in Arabic or *Muladíes* in Spanish.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] By 1000, according to Ronald Segal, some 5,000,000 of Iberia's 7,000,000 inhabitants, most of them descended from indigenous Iberian converts, were Muslim.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] There were also Sub-Saharan Africans who had been absorbed into al-Andalus to be used as soldiers and slaves.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The Berber and the sub-Saharan African soldiers were known as "tangerines" because they were imported through the Mediterranean coastal city of Tangier.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] In the 11th century, the Hindu-Arabic numeral system (base 10) had reached Europe via al-Andalus through Spanish Muslims, together with knowledge of astronomy and instruments like the astrolabe, which was first imported by Gerbert of Aurillac.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] For that reason, the numerals came to be known in Europe as Arabic numerals despite their origins in India.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] From the earliest days, the Umayyads wanted to be seen as intellectual rivals to the Abbasids and for Córdoba to have libraries and educational institutions to that of their rival, Baghdad.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Although there was a clear rivalry between the two powers, there was freedom to travel between the two caliphates, which helped spread new ideas and innovations over time.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Multilingual households were an attested phenomenon.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Initially, most of the population spoke Romance dialects.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The dialects of Iberian Romance that were spoken in al-Andalus are collectively referred to as Andalusi Romance or Mozarabic.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] What is hypothesised about these dialects is based on sparse evidence, including Romance topographical and personal names and the *kharjas* of some **muwaššaḥ** poetry.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Arabic arrived with the Umayyad conquest of Hispania in 711 and spread gradually over the following centuries, primarily through conversion to Islam.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The vernacular varieties of Arabic spoken in al-Andalus, referred to as Andalusi Arabic, were Maghrebi Arabic dialects influenced by their contact with Romance, just as Arabic influenced Spanish.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] By about 1260, following the Almohad period, most Christians had migrated to the north and Muslim territories in Iberia were reduced to the Emirate of Granada, in which more than 90% of the population had converted to Islam and Arabic-Romance bilingualism seems to have largely disappeared.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The literary traditions of Hebrew—which was used for prayer and ceremonial writings, but not for oral communication—experienced a revolution through contact with Arabic and its literary traditions.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Consuelo López Morillas writes that Jews in al-Andalus "wrote Hebrew poetry using Arabic prosodic models and adopted nearly the entire range of Arabic poetic genres and stylistic devices in Hebrew," looking to Biblical Hebrew as a source for literary expression as Muslims looked to Quranic Arabic.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Berber languages, referred to in contemporary sources as *al-lisān al-gharbī* (اللسان الغربي, Arabic for 'the western tongue'), were especially present in periods of Berber rule, particularly under the Almoravids and Almohads.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Under Almohad rule, it was compulsory to deliver the *khuṭba* (sermon) at Friday prayer in Arabic and *al-lisān al-gharbī*.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] In al-Andalus, there are 11,831 known scholars who were active and 13,730 known works that were written or transmitted from the eighth to fifteenth centuries.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Of these scholars, those who are well known and remembered in the West, such as Ibn Rushd, Ibn Hazm, or Ibn Arabi, are not necessarily the same scholars that are remembered in Islamic culture, such as Abū ʿUmar b. ʿAbd al-Barr, Abū l-Walīd al-Bājī, Ibn ʿAtịyya, Ibn al-ʿArīf, or Abū Isḥāq aš-Šāṭibī.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Poetry was considered the prime literary genre in Arabic.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Traditional forms of Arabic poetry from the Mashriq, or Muslim East, especially the monometer, monorhyme *qaṣīda* and the prosimetric *maqāma*, were adopted in al-Andalus.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The major Andalusi innovation in poetry was the 'rhyme revolution' embodied in the 10th-11th century strophic song form called the *muwaššaḥ* ('girdled'; pl.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The *muwaššaḥ* features a complex rhyme scheme usually containing five *aghsān* ('branches'; sing.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] *ghusn*), with uniform rhyme within each strophe, interspersed with *asmāṭ* ('threads for stringing pearls'; sing.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] *simṭ*) with common rhyme throughout the song, as well as a terminal *kharja*, the song's final *simṭ*, which could be in a different language.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Andalusi *zajal* was strophic poetry in Andalusi vernacular Arabic, usually associated with Ibn Quzman.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Andalusi strophic poetry had an impact on poetic expression in Western Europe, especially the Old Occitan/Provençal lyric of the troubadours, and in the wider Muslim world.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The music of al-Andalus is part of an influential musical tradition.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Ziryab, a poet and musician, who came from the Abbasid Caliphate and arrived in Córdoba in 822, played a role in Andalusi music as well as other aspects of Andalusi culture.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Poetic forms such as the *muwashshah* and its *kharja*, the *nawba*, and the *zajal* are prominent in Andalusi music.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The historian Said al-Andalus wrote that Caliph Abd-ar-Rahman III had collected libraries of books and granted patronage to scholars of medicine and "ancient sciences".
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Later, *al-Mustansir* (Al-Hakam II) went yet further, building a university and libraries in Córdoba.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Córdoba became one of the world's leading centres of medicine and philosophical debate.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] When Al-Hakam's son Hisham II took over, real power was ceded to the *hajib*, al-Mansur Ibn Abi Aamir.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Al-Mansur was a distinctly religious man and disapproved of the sciences of astronomy, logic, and especially of astrology, so much so that many books on these subjects, which had been preserved and collected at great expense by Al-Hakam II, were burned publicly.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] With Al-Mansur's death in 1002, interest in philosophy revived.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Numerous scholars emerged, including Abu Uthman Ibn Fathun, whose masterwork was the philosophical treatise "Tree of Wisdom".
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Maslamah Ibn Ahmad al-Majriti (died 1008) was an outstanding scholar in astronomy and astrology; he was an intrepid traveller who journeyed all over the Islamic world and beyond and kept in touch with the Brethren of Purity.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] He is said to have brought the 51 "Epistles of the Brethren of Purity" to *al-Andalus* and added the compendium to this work, although it is quite possible that it was added later by another scholar with the name al-Majriti.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Another book attributed to al-Majriti is the *Ghayat al-Hakim*, "The Aim of the Sage", which explored a synthesis of Platonism with Hermetic philosophy.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Its use of incantations led the book to be widely dismissed in later years, although the Sufi communities continued to study it.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] A prominent follower of al-Majriti was the philosopher and geometer Abu al-Hakam al-Kirmani who was followed, in turn, by Abu Bakr Ibn al-Sayigh, usually known in the Arab world as Ibn Bajjah, "Avempace".
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The al-Andalus philosopher Averroes (1126–1198) was the founder of the Averroism school of philosophy, and his works and commentaries influenced medieval thought in Western Europe.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Another influential al-Andalus philosopher was Ibn Tufail.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] As Jewish thought in Babylonia declined, the tolerance of *al-Andalus* made it the new centre of Jewish intellectual endeavours.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Poets and commentators like Judah Halevi (1086–1145) and Dunash ben Labrat (920–990) contributed to the cultural life of *al-Andalus*, but the area was even more important to the development of Jewish philosophy.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] In al-Andalus, Jews played a significant role in the medical sphere and achieved prominence as physicians.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Hasdai ibn Shaprut, a Jewish court official and physician in 10th-century Córdoba, was involved in the Arabic translation of Dioscorides' *Materia Medica*, collaborating with both Christian and Muslim scholars.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] In 11th-century Zaragoza, Jonah ibn Janah authored a pharmacological treatise that provided multilingual drug names and detailed discussions of weights and measures used in medicine.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] His contemporary, Jonah ibn Biklārish, compiled a medical dictionary for Zaragoza's rulers, presenting materia medica in tabular form across several languages, including Syriac, Persian, Greek, Latin, and Spanish.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Tzvi Langermann, Andalusian medicine evolved distinctive characteristics and, by the 11th century, increasingly shifted away from eastern Islamic models in favour of closer ties with North African traditions.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The influence of Andalusian medicine is evident in later Jewish figures such as Maimonides (1135–1204), whose teachers were trained in this tradition and who himself adopted its emphasis on holistic, Galenic approaches to care.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] In Córdoba, Abd ar-Rahman I built the Great Mosque of Córdoba in 785.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] It was expanded multiple times up until the 10th century, and after the Reconquista it was converted into a Catholic cathedral.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Its key features include a hypostyle hall with marble columns supporting two-tiered arches, a horseshoe-arch mihrab, ribbed domes, a courtyard (*sahn*) with gardens, and a minaret (later converted into a bell tower).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Abd ar-Rahman III, at the height of his power, began construction of Madinat al-Zahra, a luxurious palace-city to serve as a new capital.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The Umayyads also reconstructed the Roman-era bridge over the Guadalquivir River in Córdoba, while the Almohads later added the Calahorra Tower to the bridge.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The Bab al-Mardum Mosque (later converted to a church) in Toledo is a well-preserved example of a small neighbourhood mosque built at the end of the Caliphate period.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The official workshops of the Caliphate, such as those at Madinat al-Zahra, produced luxury goods for use at court or as gifts for guests, allies, and diplomats, which stimulated artistic production.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Many objects produced in the caliph's workshops later made their way into the collections of museums and Christian cathedrals in Europe.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Among the most famous objects of this period are ivory boxes which are carved with vegetal, figurative, and epigraphic motifs.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Notable surviving examples include the Pyxis of al-Mughira, the Pyxis of Zamora, and the Leyre Casket.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] During the Taifas period, art and culture continued to flourish despite the political fragmentation of al-Andalus.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The Aljaferia Palace of Zaragoza is the most significant palace preserved from this period, featuring complex ornamental arcades and stucco decoration.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] In other cities, a number of important palaces or fortresses were begun or expanded by local dynasties such as the Alcazaba of Málaga and the Alcazaba of Almería.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Other examples of architecture from around this period include the Bañuelo of Granada, an Islamic bathhouse.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] In Seville, Almohad rulers built the Great Mosque of Seville (later transformed into the Cathedral of Seville), which consisted of a hypostyle prayer hall, a courtyard (now known as the *Patio de los Naranjos* or Court of Oranges), and a massive minaret tower now known as the Giralda.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The minaret was later expanded after being converted into a bell tower for the current cathedral.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Almohad architecture promoted new forms and decorative designs such as the multifoil arch and the sebka motif, probably influenced by the Caliphate-period architecture of Córdoba.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Artists and intellectuals took refuge at Granada after the Christian kingdoms expanded significantly in the 13th century.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The palaces of the Alhambra and the Generalife in Granada reflect the culture and art of the last centuries of Muslim rule of al-Andalus.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The complex was begun by Ibn al-Ahmar, the first Nasrid emir, and the last major additions were made during the reigns of Yusuf I (1333–1353) and Muhammad V (1353–1391).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] It integrates buildings and gardens with the natural qualities of the site and is a testament to Andalusi culture and to the skills of the Muslim artisans, craftsmen, and builders of their era.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Nasrid architecture continued the earlier traditions of Andalusi architecture while also synthesising them into its own distinctive style, which had many similarities with contemporary Marinid architecture in North Africa.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] It is characterised by the use of the courtyard as a central space and basic unit around which other halls and rooms were organised.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Courtyards typically had water features at their centre, such as a reflective pool or a fountain.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Decoration was focused on the inside of buildings and was executed primarily with tile mosaics on lower walls and carved stucco on the upper walls.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Geometric patterns, vegetal motifs, and calligraphy were the main types of decorative motifs.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Additionally, "stalactite"-like sculpting, known as muqarnas, was used for three-dimensional features like vaulted ceilings, particularly during the reign of Muhammad V and after.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Numerous examples are found in the early churches of Toledo (e.g. the Church of San Román, 13th century) and in the cities of Aragon such as Zaragoza and Teruel.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Among the most famous examples is the Alcázar of Seville, the former Abbadid and Almohad palace redeveloped by Christian rulers such as Peter of Castile, who in 1364 started adding new Moorish-style sections with the help of Muslim craftsmen from Granada and Toledo.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Some surviving 13th and 14th-century Jewish synagogues were also built (or rebuilt) in Mudéjar style under Christian rule, such as the Synagogue of Santa Maria la Blanca in Toledo (rebuilt in its current form circa 1250), the Synagogue of Córdoba (1315), and the Synagogue of El Tránsito (1355–1357).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Crops produced using irrigation, along with food imported from the Middle East, provided areas around *Andalusī* cities with an agricultural economic sector that was the most advanced in Europe by far, sparking the Arab Agricultural Revolution.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] A variety of foodstuffs, spices and crops were introduced to Spain and Sicily during Arab rule, via the commercial networks of the Islamic world.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] These include sugarcane, rice, cotton, alfalfa, oranges, lemons, apricots, spinach, eggplants, carrots, saffron and bananas.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The Arabs also continued extensive cultivation and production of olive oil (the Spanish words for 'oil' and 'olive'—*aceite* and *aceituna*, respectively—are derived from the Arabic *al-zait*, meaning 'olive juice'), and pomegranates (the heraldic symbol of Granada) from classical Greco-Roman times.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Arabic influence still lingers on in Spanish cuisine through these fruits, vegetables, spices and cooking and agricultural techniques.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] These structures are still found in Andalusia province, particularly in Granada.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The confection *alfajor* (supposedly from الفاخر) has its origins in al-Andalus.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Important rulers such as Abd al-Rahman III, al-Hakam II, Hisham II, and al-Mu-tamid openly chose boys as sexual partners, and kept catamites.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Homosexual prostitution was widespread, and its customers came from higher levels of society than those of heterosexual prostitutes." The verses of Ibn Quzman describe an openly bisexual lifestyle.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Andalusi anthologies of poetry such as the *Rāyāt al-mubarrizīn wa-ghāyāt al-mumayyazīn* are known in part for their homoerotic and "abundant pederastic poetry".
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Such themes were also found in the Sephardic Jewish poetry of the time.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] In the book *Medieval Iberia: An Encyclopedia*, Daniel Eisenberg describes homosexuality as "a key symbolic issue throughout the Middle Ages in Iberia", stating that "in al-Andalus homosexual pleasures were much indulged in by the intellectual and political elite.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Both pederasty and love between adult males are found.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Although homosexual practices were never officially condoned, prohibitions against them were rarely enforced, and usually there was not even a pretense of doing so." Male homosexual relations allowed nonprocreative sexual practices and were not seen as a form of identity.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Very little is known about the homosexual behaviour of women.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Slavery existed in Muslim al-Andalus as well as in the Christian kingdoms, and both sides of the religious border followed the custom of not enslaving people of their own religion.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Consequently, Muslims were enslaved in Christian lands, while Christians and other non-Muslims were enslaved in al-Andalus.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The Moors imported white Christian slaves from the 8th century until the end of the Reconquista in the late 15th century.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The slaves were exported from the Christian section of Spain, as well as Eastern Europe (*Saqaliba*).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Saqaliba slavery in al-Andalus was especially prominent in the Caliphate of Córdoba where white slaves constituted most of the administrative personnel in the courts and palaces.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The slaves of the Caliph were often European saqaliba slaves trafficked from Northern or Eastern Europe.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] While male saqaliba could be given work in a number of tasks, such as offices in the kitchen, falconry, mint, textile workshops, the administration or the royal guard (in the case of harem guards, they were castrated), female saqaliba were placed in the harem.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The harem could contain thousands of slave concubines; the harem of Abd al-Rahman I consisted of 6,300 women.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] They were appreciated for their light skin.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] The concubines (jawaris) were educated in accomplishments to please their master, and many became known and respected for their knowledge in a variety of subjects from music to medicine.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Jawaris concubines who gave birth to a child attained the status of an *umm walad*, which meant that they could no longer be sold and were to be set free after the death of her master.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] As Andalusi cities were conquered by Leon, Castile, and other Christian Spanish kingdoms, Christian monarchs such as Alfonso X of Castile started translating the mountainous libraries of al-Andalus into Latin.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] These libraries contained translations of Ancient Greek texts, as well as new ones made by Muslims in the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] That, combined with the interaction with Muslims during the Crusades, and the Fall of Constantinople introducing Greek scholars to the west, helped launch the Renaissance.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Scientists and philosophers such as Averroes and Al-Zahrawi (fathers of rationalism and surgery, respectively) heavily inspired the Renaissance, and their ideas are still world renowned to this day.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Al Andalus has also left art and architecture and has some of the best preserved Islamic Golden Age architecture in the world, with examples including the Cathedral of Córdoba, the Alhambra, the Giralda and many more.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] As a result of the Reconquista and fall of many important Andalusi cities, substantial numbers of Andalusi migrated to the Maghreb where they found place at the courts of Maghrebi rulers.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] Many of the elite Andalusi immigrants were Arabs.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] For a variety of reasons, "Andalusi" came to be almost synonymous with "Arab" in the Maghreb.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] In the Iberian Peninsula, many Muslims were forced to convert to Christianity, particularly in the latter period of the Reconquista and following the decrees of 1502 and 1526.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/al-andalus-p02] These converts and their descendants, known as Moriscos, remained under intense persecution until their expulsion in the early 17th century.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] Paella is one of the recipes derived from a generic method to cook rice developed in the old kingdom of Valencia, now applied to the modern variants of *arroz a la valenciana*.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] The method of preparing Valencian rice has been practiced since the colonial era and can be found in Argentine, Colombian, Cuban, Filipino, Nicaraguan, Portuguese, Uruguayan and Venezuelan cuisines.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] On the other hand, Valencian paella, did not emerge until the late 19th century, among the peasants of the Horta of Valencia.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] In Spain, when a paella has other ingredients that are not "properly Valencian" it receives the informal, popular, and derogatory name of *arroz con cosas* ('rice with stuff').
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] Although there is a wide variety of *arroz a la valenciana* recipes, they all share a few commonalities.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] For example, typically, the rice is dry (without broth) and colored by various spices (originally saffron).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] Additionally it is common to include vegetables, meats and seafood.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] Although rice was probably grown in Valencia before the Moorish era, it was the Arabs who furthered its cultivation and diversification of use.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] This is reflected in both the medieval cookbooks of Christians and Muslims, in which it is evident that they were already seasoning their rice with saffron in this era; an example of this is *arròs en Cassola al forn* by Mestre Robert (16th century).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] As time went by, the culture of rice became important in Valencia, with different recipes that added vegetables and meats.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] In the colonial era, Arroz a la valenciana spread to Spanish colonies in the new world, to countries as far apart as Nicaragua or the Philippines.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] The recipe has been adapted over time to include new ingredients and to cater to American taste preferences.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] The first written mention of Arroz a la valenciana is found in a manuscript from the 18th century: *Avisos y instrucciones per lo principiant cuyiner* by the Franciscan friar Josep Orri.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] Shortly afterwards, in 1780 Friar Gerónimo de San Pelayo published a cookbook in Mexico City about Arroz a la valenciana.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] Additionally, in another Mexican cookbook called *New and Simple Art of Cooking* (1836) by Antonia Carrillo, there is a Arroz a la valenciana recipe that includes green chiles and saffron.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] The dish also appears in a cookbook published in La Habana in 1862.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] José Castro and Serrano commented that no province knows how to cook rice like Valencia.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] During a religious event in 1889 in Bergara, Spain, they served the guests Arroz a la valenciana.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] In his General Dictionary of cooking from 1892, Ángel Muro included a recipe for Arroz a la valenciana to pay homage to the *"country of rice"*.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] In the 1890s the term *arroz a la paella* ('in a frying pan') began to be used as synonymous with Arroz a la valenciana.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] In 1903, the French chef Auguste Escoffier dedicated a few pages to *riz valenciennes* in his first publication of *Le Guide Cullinaire*.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] In Bolivia, arroz a la valenciana is a very common dish that includes chicken, sometimes chorizo, and a variety of vegetables like peas, onion, tomatoes, green beans (string beans), carrots as well as potatoes from a variety of local *imilla*.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] The color of the rice comes from the use of paprika or saffron, and red chilli pepper.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] The recipe for arroz a la valenciana made its way to the Mariana Islands (formerly part of the Spanish East Indies) during the Spanish colonial era.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] Chamorro people know it as *balensiåna* and season it with achiote.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] The Chilean style of preparing arroz a la valenciana differs in its use of curry or turmeric to color the rice, although occasionally it is prepared with saffron as in the original Spanish recipe.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] Sometimes it is called "Chilean paella", and contains primarily an assortment of seafood: clams, shrimp (prawns), Chilean mussels, and clams.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] Ingredients can be adjusted to the taste profile of each location, and may include sausages or chicken.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] When using only vegetables, it is referred to as "arroz a la jardinera".
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] Arroz a la valenciana is a typical coastal dish in Colombia.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] It usually includes pork or chicken, alongside fish and seafood, and is mainly seasoned with saffron.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] In the Philippines, *arroz a la valenciana* is usually known simply as *arroz valenciana* (Tagalog: *aros balensiyana*).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] It is common in the regional cuisines of the Tagalog, Hiligaynon and Negrense people.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] It is usually regarded as a subtype of a class of Filipino dishes known as *paelya* (derived from the Valencian paella with influences from pre-colonial adaptations of biryani).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] *Paelya* tends to refer to the dishes with more expensive ingredients, while *arroz valenciana* refers to dishes with simpler ingredients, leading to it being dubbed as the "*paella* of the poor".
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] It is traditionally served during the Christmas *noche buena* as well as in *fiestas* (patronal festivals) and other special occasions.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] In contrast to Spanish and Latin American versions, it is typically made with local glutinous rice varieties that fall within the class termed *malagkít* (“sticky”).
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] The vegetables vary from one place to another, including onions, tomatoes, bell pepper, green peas, carrots, and parsley.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] The meat component is usually chicken and chorizo de Bilbao (a Filipino type of sausage), but numerous other types of protein can be used or added, ranging from boiled eggs, pork, beef, duck, and seafood.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] In addition, coconut milk – an indispensable ingredient in the country – may be used in the cooking process.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] Like other types of Filipino *paelya*, *arroz valenciana* rarely uses saffron.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] Instead it characteristically uses *achuete* (anatto), *luyang diláw* (turmeric), or *kasubhâ* (safflower) to add color to the rice.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] Like in some parts of Latin America, the dish may also have alcohol.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] Common spirits include white wine or beer, while butter is sometimes used instead of oil.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] The Nicaraguan recipe of arroz a la valenciana is different from the Spanish original, since it includes butter instead of oil, onion, tomato sauce, *chiltoma* (sweet pepper), and other vegetables according to the preferences of the chef.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] The meats used are usually chicken, ham or choricitos.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] It is one of the typical small plates of rice in Nicaragua.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] At times it is called "arroz de piñata", as it is often served during children's birthday celebrations colloquialy called "piñatas".
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] It is usually prepared with beer, along with white wine.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] In El Salvador, arroz a la valenciana usually includes hard-boiled eggs and several pieces of chicken, like the breast, gizzard or liver.
[src:arroz-a-la-valenciana/arroz-a-la-valenciana] A variety of vegetables are added, like onion, peas (sweet peas), sweet corn (maize), or carrots.
